    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The overrepresentation of certain racial groups in the US prison system is largely due to systemic biases and discriminatory practices. Factors such as racial profiling, harsher sentencing laws for minority groups, and socio-economic disparities contribute to this issue. Additionally, there is a disproportionate targeting of minority communities by law enforcement, leading to higher arrest rates and subsequent incarceration. These systemic issues perpetuate a cycle of inequality and injustice within the criminal justice system.",
